\hypertarget{introduction}{%
\chapter*{Introduction}\label{introduction}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Introduction}

This handout is designed for the use with MEM5220 - Applied Econometrics at \href{https://taltech.ee/en/department-economics-and-finance}{Tallinn University of Technology, Department of Economics and Finance}.

\hypertarget{prerequisites}{%
\section*{Prerequisites}\label{prerequisites}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Prerequisites}

A basic knowledge of the R \citep{team2013r} programming language is required.

In order to reproduce the examples in this script you need the statistical software package R. Additionally I recommend using the \href{https://www.rstudio.com}{RStudio} integrated developer environment (IDE) which will improve your R working experience.

\hypertarget{installation-of-r-and-rstudio}{%
\subsection*{Installation of R and RStudio}\label{installation-of-r-and-rstudio}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Installation of R and RStudio}

Go to the following webpages and download the software adequate for Your operating system:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \href{http://cran.r-project.org}{The Statistical Software Package R:}
\item
  The GUI \href{https://www.rstudio.com}{RStudio:}
\end{enumerate}

Install R first and then proceed with RStudio. Afterwards start RStudio. For accessing packages and datasets from \href{https://github.com/}{github} we need to install the \textbf{devtools} package. On Windows, download and install \href{https://cran.r-project.org/bin/windows/Rtools/}{Rtools}, and devtools takes care of the rest. On Mac, install the Xcode command line tools. On Linux, install the R development package, usually called r-devel or r-base-dev.

\hypertarget{resources}{%
\section*{Resources}\label{resources}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Resources}

Our primary resource is \citet{heiss2016using} \footnote{Heiss (2016) builds on the popular Introductory Econometrics by Wooldridge (2016) and demonstrates how to replicate the applications discussed therein using R.}. The book is available as free \href{http://www.urfie.net/read.html}{online} version. For theoretical concepts I refer to \citet{wooldridge2015introductory}\footnote{\href{https://books.google.ee/books/about/Introductory_Econometrics_A_Modern_Appro.html?id=wUF4BwAAQBAJ\&source=kp_cover\&redir_esc=y}{Introductory Econometrics: A Modern Approach}.}.
For the timeseries part of the course a good reference material is \href{https://www.cambridge.org/pt/academic/subjects/economics/finance/introductory-econometrics-finance-3rd-edition?format=PB\&isbn=9781107661455}{Introductory Econometircs for Finance}.

\hypertarget{attribution}{%
\subsection*{Attribution}\label{attribution}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Attribution}

This lecture material would not possible without many other open-source econometrics teaching materials and of course the R package developers. In addition to the main resources, examples and code of this workbook have been drawn from a number of free econometrics eBooks, blogs, R-vignette help pages and other researchers teaching materials.

Chapter 1.1.2 Simulating SLR is based on \citet{heiss2016using} but adds parts of \citet{dalpiaz2016} and \citet{colonescu2018} teaching materials. Chapter 1.2.2 includes additional material from \citet{Hanck2018}. Chapter 1.4 Heteroskedasticity has been amended with material from \citet{Rodrigues2018} blog. The time series part is closely related to the teaching material of Andres Vörk. The finite distributed lags model is adapted from Constantin Colonescu.

\hypertarget{software-information-and-conventions}{%
\section*{Software information and conventions}\label{software-information-and-conventions}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Software information and conventions}

The R session information when compiling this book is shown below:

I do not add prompts (\texttt{\textgreater{}} and \texttt{+}) to R source code in this book, and I comment out the text output with two hashes \texttt{\#\#} by default, as you can see from the R session information above. This is for your convenience when you want to copy and run the code (the text output will be ignored since it is commented out).

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  R code blocks and their output appear in a gray background. E.g.,
\end{itemize}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DecValTok{2} \SpecialCharTok{+} \DecValTok{2} \SpecialCharTok{==} \DecValTok{5}
\NormalTok{[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{] }\ConstantTok{FALSE}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Functions and inline code are in a typewriter font and followed by parentheses, all atop a gray background (e.g., \texttt{brm()}).
\item
  When I want to make explicit the package a given function comes from, I insert the double-colon operator \texttt{::} between the package name and the function (e.g., \texttt{tidybayes::mode\_hdi()}).
\end{itemize}

Package names are in bold text (e.g., \textbf{rmarkdown}). Content with \textbf{Note}, \textbf{Your turn} and \textbf{Overthinking} is surrounded by two horizontal lines. \textbf{Overthinking} sections serve as additional information for the interested reader but will not be covered in detail in class.

\hypertarget{pooled-cross-sections}{%
\section{Pooled cross-sections}\label{pooled-cross-sections}}

Pooled cross sections consist of random samples from the same population at different points in time.

\textbf{Changes to return to education and teh gender wage gap}

The data set \texttt{cps78\_85} includes two pooled cross-sections for the year 1978 and 1985. The dummy variable \textbf{y85} is equal to one for observations in 1985 and 0 for observations in 1978.

We estimate a model for

\[
\log(w) = \beta_0 + \delta_{0}y85 + \beta_1 educ + \delta_{1} (y85 \times educ) +  \beta_{2} exper +  \beta_{3} \frac{exper^2}{100} + \beta_{4} union + \beta_{5}female + \delta_{2} (y85 \times female) + \epsilon
\]

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{data}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"cps78\_85"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{package=}\StringTok{"wooldridge"}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{attach}\NormalTok{(cps78\_85)}
\FunctionTok{head}\NormalTok{(cps78\_85)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{organizing-panel-data}{%
\section{Organizing Panel Data}\label{organizing-panel-data}}

For the calculations used by panel data methods, we have to make sure that the data is systemically organized. Usually panel data comes in a \emph{long} structure where each row corresponds to one combination of \(i\) and \(t\). We have to introduce an index variable to define which observations belong together. In addition to the index variable for the cross-sectional unit, an index variable for the time dimension \(t\) can also be specified.

The \textbf{plm} and the \textbf{felm} package are the widely used panel data packages in R. For certain panel data model classes (multilevel and hierarchical models) the \textbf{lme4} package is most powerful. The currently fasted panel data routines in R are implemented \textbf{fixest} \footnote{The package \texttt{lme4} is widely used for political science panel data models but also for computational biologists applications. Another good package doing panel data analysis is \texttt{panelr}. The \texttt{brms} package allows fitting certain panel data models using a Bayesian approach.}. One of the many packages that help you analyze panel data using \texttt{dplyr} style of manipulating the data is the package \textbf{pmdplyr}.

Certain packages use a specific panel data type class (pdata.frame) such as the plm package whereas others work with the standard data.frame type, as long as unique panel ids (indexes) are provided.

\hypertarget{organizing-panel-data-with-the-plm-package}{%
\subsection{Organizing Panel Data with the plm package}\label{organizing-panel-data-with-the-plm-package}}

For unbalanced panels I can specify a panel data frame with \texttt{pdata.frame(mydf,\ index\ =\ c("ivar",\ "tvar"))} and for balanced panels one can simply define the index \texttt{pdata.frame(mydf,\ index\ =\ n)}.

\hypertarget{panel-specific-computations}{%
\subsection{Panel specific computations}\label{panel-specific-computations}}

The the \textbf{plm} and the \textbf{pmdply} can be used to perform panel specific computations. We focus on the methods provided by the \textbf{plm} package.

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.16}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.53}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.31}}@{}}
\toprule
Code & Description & Formula \\
\midrule
\endhead
l = lag(x) & Lag & \(l_{it} = x_{it}-1\) \\
d = diff(x) & Difference \(\Delta x_{it}\) & \(d_{it} = x_{it} - x_{it-1}\) \\
b = between(x) & Between transformation \(\bar{x_{i}}\) (length \(n\)) & \(b_i = \frac{1}{T_i}\sum^{T_i}_{t=1}x_{it}\) \\
B = Between(x) & Between transformation \(\bar{x_{i}}\) (length \(N\)) & \(B_{it} = b_i\) \\
w = within(x) & Within transformation (demeaning) \(\ddot{x}_{it}\) & \(w_{it} = x_{it} - B_{it}\) \\
\bottomrule
\end{longtable}

\hypertarget{fixed-effects-estimation}{%
\section{Fixed Effects Estimation}\label{fixed-effects-estimation}}

Instead of first differencing, we get rid of the unobserved individual effect \(a_i\) using the within transformation. Using the \texttt{model\ =\ "within} argument from the \texttt{plm} function, we obtain degrees of freedom, which are adjusted for the demeaning which also corrects the variance-covariance matrix and standard errors.

\hypertarget{random-effects-estimation}{%
\section{Random Effects Estimation}\label{random-effects-estimation}}

The random effects (RE) model assumes that the unobserved effects of \(a_i\) are independent of (or at least uncorrelated) with the regressors \(x_{itj}\) for all \(t\) and \(j=1,\dots,k\). Therefore, our main motivation for using FD or FE disappears as OLS can consistently estimate the models parameters.
However, like in the situation with heteroskedasticity and autocorrelation, we can obtain more efficient estimates if we take into account the structure of the variances and covariances of the error term.

To estimate a RE model using \texttt{plm}, the argument option is set to \texttt{model\ =\ "random"}.

Fixed effects might be extracted easily using \texttt{fixef}. By setting the type argument, the fixed effects may be returned in levels (``level''), as deviations from the first value of the index (``dfirst''), or as deviations from the overall mean (``dmean''). If the argument vcov was specified, the standard errors (stored as attribute ``se'' in the return value) are the respective robust standard errors.

\hypertarget{hausman-test}{%
\subsection{Hausman test}\label{hausman-test}}

The RE estimator needs stronger assumptions to be consistent than the FE estimator. On the other hand, it is more efficient if in these assumptions hold and we can include time constant regressors. A widely used test of this additional assumption is the Hausman test.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{phtest}\NormalTok{(reg.fe, reg.re)}

\NormalTok{    Hausman Test}

\NormalTok{data}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{  lwage }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}} \FunctionTok{I}\NormalTok{(exper}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ married }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ union }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ yr}
\NormalTok{chisq }\OtherTok{=} \FloatTok{26.361}\NormalTok{, df }\OtherTok{=} \DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{, p}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value }\OtherTok{=} \FloatTok{0.003284}
\NormalTok{alternative hypothesis}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{ one model is inconsistent}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

With a p-value of 0.003, the null hypthosis of the RE model being consistent is rejected.
Robust Hausman test

The presence of heteroskedasdicity can matter for the outcome of the Hausman test.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{data}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"RDSpillovers"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{package =} \StringTok{"pder"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{pehs }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{pdata.frame}\NormalTok{(RDSpillovers, }\AttributeTok{index =} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"id"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"year"}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{ehsfm }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ lny }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ lnl }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ lnk }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ lnrd }\CommentTok{\# just the random effects model formula to the vcov}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Regression based Hausman test

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{phtest}\NormalTok{(ehsfm, pehs, }\AttributeTok{method =} \StringTok{"aux"}\NormalTok{) }

\NormalTok{    Regression}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{based Hausman test}

\NormalTok{data}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{  ehsfm}
\NormalTok{chisq }\OtherTok{=} \FloatTok{53.281}\NormalTok{, df }\OtherTok{=} \DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, p}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value }\OtherTok{=} \FloatTok{1.597e{-}11}
\NormalTok{alternative hypothesis}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{ one model is inconsistent}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Regression based Hausman test with robust estimator for the covariance.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{phtest}\NormalTok{(ehsfm, pehs, }\AttributeTok{method =} \StringTok{"aux"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{vcov =}\NormalTok{ vcovHC) }

\NormalTok{    Regression}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{based Hausman test, vcov}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{ vcovHC}

\NormalTok{data}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{  ehsfm}
\NormalTok{chisq }\OtherTok{=} \FloatTok{2.3056}\NormalTok{, df }\OtherTok{=} \DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, p}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value }\OtherTok{=} \FloatTok{0.5114}
\NormalTok{alternative hypothesis}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{ one model is inconsistent}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The robust version of the Hausman test does not reject the random effects hypothesis anymore.The robust version of the Hausman test does not reject the random effects hypothesis anymore.

\tightlist
\item
  Wald Tests for Serial correlation using \emph{within} and First-difference Estimators
\end{itemize}

This test is applicable to an FE panel model and in particular to ``short'' panels with small \(T\) and large \(N\).

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{data}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"EmplUK"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{package =} \StringTok{"plm"}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{pwartest}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(emp) }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}} \FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(wage) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(capital), }\AttributeTok{data =}\NormalTok{ EmplUK)}

\NormalTok{    Wooldridge}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}s test for serial correlation in FE panels}

\StringTok{data:  plm.model}
\StringTok{F = 312.3, df1 = 1, df2 = 889, p{-}value \textless{} 2.2e{-}16}
\StringTok{alternative hypothesis: serial correlation}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We strongly reject the null of no serial correlation. The evidence of serial correlation is so strong that we should think whether the residuals are stationary at all. A first difference specification might be preferable.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{pwfdtest}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(emp) }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}} \FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(wage) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(capital), }\AttributeTok{data =}\NormalTok{ EmplUK)}

\NormalTok{    Wooldridge}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}s first{-}difference test for serial correlation in panels}

\StringTok{data:  plm.model}
\StringTok{F = 1.5251, df1 = 1, df2 = 749, p{-}value = 0.2172}
\StringTok{alternative hypothesis: serial correlation in differenced errors}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We can't reject the null hypothesis, indicating that a first difference specification removes the residual serial correlation.

However, results are not always clear cut.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{W.fd }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{matrix}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{ncol =} \DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{nrow =}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{H0 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"fd"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"fe"}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{dimnames}\NormalTok{(W.fd) }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{list}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"test"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"p{-}value"}\NormalTok{), H0)}
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{(i }\ControlFlowTok{in}\NormalTok{ H0) \{}
\NormalTok{    mytest }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{pwfdtest}\NormalTok{(fm, Rice, }\AttributeTok{h0 =}\NormalTok{ i)}
\NormalTok{    W.fd[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, i] }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ mytest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{statistic}
\NormalTok{    W.fd[}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, i] }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ mytest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{p.value}
\NormalTok{    \}}
\FunctionTok{round}\NormalTok{(W.fd, }\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{              fd        fe}
\NormalTok{test    }\FloatTok{176.4155} \FloatTok{19.574707}
\NormalTok{p}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value   }\FloatTok{0.0000}  \FloatTok{0.000011}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Both specifications reject the null. Whichever estimate you run, you will have serially correlated errors. In that case it is advisable to use an autocorrelation-robust covariance matrix.

\hypertarget{cross-sectional-dependence}{%
\subsection{Cross-sectional dependence}\label{cross-sectional-dependence}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Pesaran CD test for cross-sectional dependence in panels
\end{itemize}

Cross-sectional dependence can arise if individuals respond to common shocks or if spatial diffusion processes are present (``shock'' affecting individuals on a measure of distance).

\FunctionTok{data}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"HousePricesUS"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{package =} \StringTok{"pder"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{php }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{pdata.frame}\NormalTok{(HousePricesUS)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{cbind}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"rho"}   \OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{pcdtest}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{diff}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(php}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{price)), }\AttributeTok{test =} \StringTok{"rho"}\NormalTok{)}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{statistic,}
      \StringTok{"|rho|"} \OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{pcdtest}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{diff}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(php}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{price)), }\AttributeTok{test =} \StringTok{"absrho"}\NormalTok{)}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{statistic)}
\NormalTok{          rho     }\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{rho}\SpecialCharTok{|}
\NormalTok{rho }\FloatTok{0.3942212} \FloatTok{0.4246933}
\end{Highlighting}

\hypertarget{dummy-variable-regression-and-correlated-random-effects}{%
\section{Dummy Variable Regression and Correlated Random Effects}\label{dummy-variable-regression-and-correlated-random-effects}}

We can get the FE parameter estimates in two other ways than the within transformation. The dummy variable equation uses OLS on the original variables instead of the transformed ones. But it adds \(n-1\) dummy variables (or \(n\) dummies and removes the constant), one for each cross-sectional unit \(i = 1, \dots, n\). The simplest (although not the most computationally efficient) way to implement this in R is to use the cross-sectional index as another factor variable. The third way is the correlated random effects (CRE) approach. Instead of assuming that the individual affects \(a_i\) are independent on the regressors \(x_{itj}\), it is assumed that they only depend on the averages over time \(\bar{x}_{ij} = \frac{1}{T_{i}} \sum^{2}_{i=1}T_{i}\).

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{data}\NormalTok{(wagepan, }\AttributeTok{package=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}wooldridge\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{\# Generate pdata.frame:}
\NormalTok{wagepan.p }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{pdata.frame}\NormalTok{(wagepan, }\AttributeTok{index=}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"nr"}\NormalTok{,}\StringTok{"year"}\NormalTok{) )}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]

Another advantage of the CRE approach is that we can add time-constant regressors to the model. Since we cannot control for average values of \(\bar{x}_{ij}\) for these variables, they have to be uncorrelated with \(a_i\) for consistent estimation of \emph{their} coefficients. For the other coefficients of the time-varying variables, we still don't need these additional RE assumptions.

\hypertarget{robust-clustered-standard-errors}{%
\section{Robust (Clustered) Standard Errors}\label{robust-clustered-standard-errors}}

Under the RE assumptions, OLS is inefficient but consistent. Instead of using RE, we could use OLS but would have to adjust the standard errors for the fact the composite error term \(v_{it} = \alpha_{i}+ u_{it}\) is correlated over time because of the constant individual effect \(\alpha_{i}\). In fact, the variance-covariance matrix could be more complex than the RE assumptions with i.i.d. \(u_{it}\) implies. These errors terms could be serially correlated and/ or heteroscedastic. This would invalidate the standard errors not only of OLS but also of FD, FE, RE and CRE.

Especially in large cross-sectional data, formulas exist for the variance-covariance matrix for panel data that are robust with respect to heteroskedasticity and \emph{arbitrary} correlations of the error term within a cross-sectional unit (or ``cluster'').

Different versions of clustered variance-covariance matrix can be computed with the command \texttt{vcovHC} from the \texttt{plm} package\footnote{Note that \texttt{vcovHC} from the \texttt{plm} package is different from the \texttt{vcovHC} function of the \texttt{sandwich} package.}. The \texttt{fixest} package also handles multiway clustered errors.

The next chunk estimates a familiar FD regression but also reports the regression table with clustered standard errors and respective \(t\) statistics in addition to the non-adjusted standard errors.

\hypertarget{unrestricted-generalized-least-squares}{%
\section{Unrestricted Generalized Least Squares}\label{unrestricted-generalized-least-squares}}

The GLS estimator is a matrix-weighted average of the \emph{between} and the \emph{within} estimator. The combination of both estimators is more efficient than either of these alone.

The ``random effect'' equivalent, general GLS, is estimated by specifying the \emph{model} argument as \texttt{pooling}\footnote{The ``random'' effect is better termed ``general FGSLS'' models, as in fact it does not have a proper random effects structure.}.

\hypertarget{unbalanced-panels}{%
\section{Unbalanced panels}\label{unbalanced-panels}}

For unbalanced panels, the number of observations for each individual is now individual specific (\(T_{n}\)). Compared to the balanced panel case, three complications appear:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  The covariance matrix of the errors cannot be written anymore as a linear combination of idempotent and mutually orthogonal matrices.
\item
  For models with just one fixed effect, the \emph{within} transformation still consists of removing the individual mean from the variable. On the contrary, for models with multiple fixed effects, the \emph{within} transformation is not obtained by performing the difference with the individual and time means (or means of another FE), as in the balanced panel case, but requires more tedious matrix algebra.
\item
  To estimate the components of the variance, the quadratic forms of the residuals is calculated as in the balanced panel case, but there is no obvious choice of the denominator.
  The \emph{Tilerseries} dataset contains data on the weekly production of cement floor tiles for 25 small-scale tileries in 1982-1983. The data are observed for 66 weeks in total and aggregated on periods of three weeks.
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{maximum-liklihood-estimator}{%
\section{Maximum Liklihood Estimator}\label{maximum-liklihood-estimator}}

An alternative to OLS estimator is the maximum likelihood estimator. Contrary to the GLS estimator, the parameters are not estimated sequentially but simultaniously.

The maximum likelihood estimator is available in the \textbf{pglm} package. We have to specify the distribution of the errors of the model by setting the \emph{family} argument.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{data}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"RiceFarms"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{package =} \StringTok{"splm"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{Rice }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{pdata.frame}\NormalTok{(RiceFarms, }\AttributeTok{index =} \StringTok{"id"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

                \AttributeTok{data =}\NormalTok{ Rice, }\AttributeTok{family =}\NormalTok{ gaussian)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{dynamic-panel-data-models}{%
\section{Dynamic Panel Data Models}\label{dynamic-panel-data-models}}

In the context of panel data, we usually must deal with unobserved heterogeneity by applying the within (demeaning) transformation, as in one-way fixed effects models, or by taking first differences if the second dimension of the panel is a proper time series.

The ability of first differencing to remove unobserved heterogeneity also underlies the family of estimators that have been developed for dynamic panel data (DPD) models. These models contain one or more lagged dependent variables, allowing for the modelling of a partial adjustment mechanism.

The econometric community distinguishes roughly between two types of dynamic panel data models:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Micro-panels} where \(N>>T\)
\item
  \textbf{Macro-panels} where \(N \leq T\)
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{micro-panel}{%
\subsection{Micro panel}\label{micro-panel}}

Dynamic panel data models are estimated using the GMM estimator suggested by \citet{Arellano1991}, utilizing lagged endogenous regressors after a first-differences transformation.

Through the whole chapter we will use a dataset capturing the relationship between Democracy and Income from a study by Acemoglu, Johnson, Robinson, and Yared (2008). The data is spread across two different datasets, containing first observations for 211 countries for a period of 1950 to 2000 and data from 1850 to 2000 for 25 countries.

\begin{Shaded}

\FunctionTok{data}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"DemocracyIncome"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{package =} \StringTok{"pder"}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{data}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"DemocracyIncome25"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{package =} \StringTok{"pder"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Estimate an OLS model with \emph{within} time fixed effects.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{mco }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{plm}\NormalTok{(democracy }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy) }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income), }\CommentTok{\# note he lag}
\NormalTok{           DemocracyIncome, }\AttributeTok{index =} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"country"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"year"}\NormalTok{), }
           \AttributeTok{model =} \StringTok{"within"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{effect =} \StringTok{"time"}\NormalTok{,}
           \AttributeTok{subset =}\NormalTok{ sample }\SpecialCharTok{==} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{coef}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{summary}\NormalTok{(mco))}
\NormalTok{                 Estimate  Std. Error  t}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value      }\FunctionTok{Pr}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}}\ErrorTok{|}\NormalTok{t}\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy) }\FloatTok{0.70636982} \FloatTok{0.024293078} \FloatTok{29.07700} \FloatTok{6.978578e{-}133}
\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income)    }\FloatTok{0.07231846} \FloatTok{0.008342943}  \FloatTok{8.66822}  \FloatTok{1.915051e{-}17}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The coefficients for democracy show a high persistence. Lagged income also shows a high significantly positive influence on the democracy index. However, we know the OLS estimator suffers from a positive bias.

Next estimate a two-way fixed effects model.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{within }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{update}\NormalTok{(mco, }\AttributeTok{effect =} \StringTok{"twoways"}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{coef}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{summary}\NormalTok{(within))}
\NormalTok{                 Estimate Std. Error    t}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value     }\FunctionTok{Pr}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}}\ErrorTok{|}\NormalTok{t}\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy) }\FloatTok{0.37862837} \FloatTok{0.03344426} \FloatTok{11.3211770} \FloatTok{1.251513e{-}27}
\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income)    }\FloatTok{0.01041497} \FloatTok{0.02640112}  \FloatTok{0.3944898} \FloatTok{6.933266e{-}01}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

With respect to the OLS model, the autoregressive coefficient is smaller. After introducing country fixed effects, the coefficient of income is close to 0 and not significant anymore.

Now we estimate the model with the Anderson and Hsiao (1982) estimator. For that one must specify that both the regressand and regressors are differenced and that the lagged endogenous variable in differences is instrumented wit the endogenous in levels lagged two periods. Acemoglu et al.~(2008) use the second lag of per capita income as a second instrument.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{ahsiao }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{plm}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{diff}\NormalTok{(democracy) }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{diff}\NormalTok{(democracy)) }\SpecialCharTok{+} 
\NormalTok{              plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{diff}\NormalTok{(income)) }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ year }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \DecValTok{1}  \SpecialCharTok{|} 
\NormalTok{              plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ year }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }
\NormalTok{              DemocracyIncome, }\AttributeTok{index =} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"country"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"year"}\NormalTok{),}
              \AttributeTok{model =} \StringTok{"pooling"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{subset =}\NormalTok{ sample }\SpecialCharTok{==} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{coef}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{summary}\NormalTok{(ahsiao))[}\DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, ]}
\NormalTok{                            Estimate Std. Error    z}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value     }\FunctionTok{Pr}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}}\ErrorTok{|}\NormalTok{z}\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{diff}\NormalTok{(democracy))  }\FloatTok{0.4686593}  \FloatTok{0.1181956}  \FloatTok{3.9651163} \FloatTok{7.336016e{-}05}
\NormalTok{plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{diff}\NormalTok{(income))    }\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\FloatTok{0.1035793}  \FloatTok{0.3048546} \SpecialCharTok{{-}}\FloatTok{0.3397662} \FloatTok{7.340326e{-}01}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Anderson and Hsiao (1982)'s model being consistent, one expects the estimated autoregressive coefficient to be comprised between that of the \emph{within} model (biased downwards) and that of the OLS model (biased upwards).

\hypertarget{gmm-estimation-of-the-differenced-model}{%
\subsection{GMM Estimation of the Differenced Model}\label{gmm-estimation-of-the-differenced-model}}

The IV approach presented in the previous section is inefficient for two reasons:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  It does not account for the correlation induced into the errors by first-differencing
\item
  There are further valid instruments available
\end{enumerate}

The \textbf{GMM} estimation of a panel data model is performed through the \texttt{plm::pgmm()} command.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{diff1 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{pgmm}\NormalTok{(democracy }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy) }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income) }\SpecialCharTok{|} \CommentTok{\# regulars regressors}
\NormalTok{              plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy, }\DecValTok{2}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{99}\NormalTok{)}\SpecialCharTok{|} \CommentTok{\#  GMM instruments}
\NormalTok{              plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{), }\CommentTok{\# "normal" instruments}
\NormalTok{              DemocracyIncome, }\AttributeTok{index=}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"country"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"year"}\NormalTok{), }
              \AttributeTok{model=}\StringTok{"onestep"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{effect=}\StringTok{"twoways"}\NormalTok{,  }\CommentTok{\# Estimation procedure}
              \AttributeTok{subset =}\NormalTok{ sample }\SpecialCharTok{==} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{coef}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{summary}\NormalTok{(diff1))}
\NormalTok{                       Estimate Std. Error   z}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value     }\FunctionTok{Pr}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}}\ErrorTok{|}\NormalTok{z}\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy)  }\FloatTok{0.50499446} \FloatTok{0.09049045}  \FloatTok{5.580638} \FloatTok{2.396373e{-}08}
\NormalTok{plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income)    }\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\FloatTok{0.09010807} \FloatTok{0.08029127} \SpecialCharTok{{-}}\FloatTok{1.122265} \FloatTok{2.617498e{-}01}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The two-step model is obtained by setting the \texttt{model} argument to \texttt{twosteps}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{diff2 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{update}\NormalTok{(diff1, }\AttributeTok{model =} \StringTok{"twosteps"}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{coef}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{summary}\NormalTok{(diff2))}
\NormalTok{                  Estimate Std. Error    z}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value     }\FunctionTok{Pr}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}}\ErrorTok{|}\NormalTok{z}\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy) }\FloatTok{0.554007280} \FloatTok{0.10783032} \FloatTok{5.13776889} \FloatTok{2.780195e{-}07}
\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income)    }\FloatTok{0.001843585} \FloatTok{0.06053787} \FloatTok{0.03045341} \FloatTok{9.757054e{-}01}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

All available lags have been used and the number of instruments is sizeable. The results are near those of the Anderson and Hsiao (1982) model.

\hypertarget{gmm-estimator-in-differences-and-levels}{%
\subsection{GMM Estimator in Differences and Levels}\label{gmm-estimator-in-differences-and-levels}}

The main drawback of the difference \textbf{GMM} estimator is that lagged variables of the dependent variable are often very weakly correlated with its lagged first difference. To solve this weak instruments problem, one can add moment conditions on the model in levels.

System GMM

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{sys2 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{pgmm}\NormalTok{(democracy }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy) }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income) }\SpecialCharTok{|}  \CommentTok{\# regressors }
\NormalTok{             plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy, }\DecValTok{2}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{99}\NormalTok{)}\SpecialCharTok{|}  \CommentTok{\# GMM instruments}
\NormalTok{              plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{), }\CommentTok{\# "normal" instruments}
\NormalTok{             DemocracyIncome, }\AttributeTok{index =} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"country"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"year"}\NormalTok{), }
             \AttributeTok{model =} \StringTok{"twosteps"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{effect =} \StringTok{"twoways"}\NormalTok{,}
             \AttributeTok{transformation =} \StringTok{"ld"}\NormalTok{) }\CommentTok{\# System GMM level and differences}
\FunctionTok{coef}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{summary}\NormalTok{(sys2))}
\NormalTok{                     Estimate Std. Error   z}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value     }\FunctionTok{Pr}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}}\ErrorTok{|}\NormalTok{z}\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy) }\FloatTok{0.6175939} \FloatTok{0.05713917} \FloatTok{10.808591} \FloatTok{3.134483e{-}27}
\NormalTok{plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income)    }\FloatTok{0.1199633} \FloatTok{0.01791565}  \FloatTok{6.696003} \FloatTok{2.141970e{-}11}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The autoregressive coefficient obtained with the difference and the system models are close. The income coefficient is now significantly positive and much larger than previously.

\hypertarget{robust-estimation-of-the-coefficients-covariance}{%
\subsection{Robust Estimation of the Coefficients' Covariance}\label{robust-estimation-of-the-coefficients-covariance}}

The two-steps estimator, albeit being robust to the presence of heteroskedasticity and/ or autocorrelation, depends still on the residuals of the one-step model. The estimator is therefore still biased and requires a robust estimator adjustment for the variance.

The function \texttt{vcov} computes the ``classical'' inconsistent version of the variance.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{diag}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{vcov}\NormalTok{(diff2)))[}\DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]}
\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy)    }\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income) }
    \FloatTok{0.04794953}     \FloatTok{0.04645903} 
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The function \texttt{vcovHC} computes the the robust version

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{diag}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{vcovHC}\NormalTok{(diff2)))[}\DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]}
\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy)    }\FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income) }
    \FloatTok{0.10783032}     \FloatTok{0.06053787} 
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

One can see that in this example the classical variance formula seems to be biased downwards. The robust standard errors are clearly superior.

\hypertarget{overidentifcation-test}{%
\subsection{Overidentifcation test}\label{overidentifcation-test}}

Similar to a general IV approach we can test for overidentification using Sargan-Hansen test

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{sargan}\NormalTok{(diff2)}

\NormalTok{    Sargan test}

\NormalTok{data}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{  democracy }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}} \FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income) }\SpecialCharTok{|} \FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy, }\DecValTok{2}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{99}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{  ...}
\NormalTok{chisq }\OtherTok{=} \FloatTok{49.881}\NormalTok{, df }\OtherTok{=} \DecValTok{44}\NormalTok{, p}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value }\OtherTok{=} \FloatTok{0.251}
\NormalTok{alternative hypothesis}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{ overidentifying restrictions not valid}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

For the difference model the hypothesis of moments's validity is not rejected.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{sargan}\NormalTok{(sys2)}

\NormalTok{    Sargan test}

\NormalTok{data}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{  democracy }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}} \FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income) }\SpecialCharTok{|} \FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy, }\DecValTok{2}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{99}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{  ...}
\NormalTok{chisq }\OtherTok{=} \FloatTok{55.678}\NormalTok{, df }\OtherTok{=} \DecValTok{54}\NormalTok{, p}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value }\OtherTok{=} \FloatTok{0.4114}
\NormalTok{alternative hypothesis}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{ overidentifying restrictions not valid}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Also for the system GMM model the hypothesis of moment's validity is not rejected.

\hypertarget{error-serial-correlation-test}{%
\subsection{Error Serial Correlation Test}\label{error-serial-correlation-test}}

The GMM is not consistent unless the moment conditions are verified, which, in particular, implies that the innovations are serially correlated.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{plm}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{mtest}\NormalTok{(diff2, }\AttributeTok{order =} \DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{    Arellano}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{Bond autocorrelation test of degree }\DecValTok{2}

\NormalTok{data}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{  democracy }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}} \FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(income) }\SpecialCharTok{|} \FunctionTok{lag}\NormalTok{(democracy, }\DecValTok{2}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{99}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{  ...}
\NormalTok{normal }\OtherTok{=} \FloatTok{0.88094}\NormalTok{, p}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{value }\OtherTok{=} \FloatTok{0.3784}
\NormalTok{alternative hypothesis}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{ autocorrelation present}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The hypothesis of no serial correlation is not rejected.

\hypertarget{macro-panel}{%
\subsection{Macro panel}\label{macro-panel}}

Macro panel models are an advanced topic and are therefore not covered in this course.

\hypertarget{binarymodels}{%
\chapter{Qualitative and LDV Models}\label{binarymodels}}

To load the dataset and necessary functions:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# This function 1. checks if the packages are installed. 2. It installs the packages if they were not in the list of installed packages. 3. It loads the packages into the workspace}
\CommentTok{\# devtools::install\_github("ccolonescu/PoEdata")}
\NormalTok{PACKAGES}\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}
            \StringTok{"tidyverse"}\NormalTok{,  }\CommentTok{\# for data manipulation and ggplots}
            \StringTok{"broom"}\NormalTok{,  }\CommentTok{\# Tidy regression output}
            \StringTok{"tidymodels"}\NormalTok{, }\CommentTok{\# packages for modeling and machine learning using }
            \StringTok{"Hmisc"}\NormalTok{, }\CommentTok{\# Harrell Miscellaneous functions}

            \StringTok{"car"}\NormalTok{, }\CommentTok{\# Companion to applied regression}

Binary dependent variables are frequently studied in applied economics. Because a dummy variable \(y\) can only take values 0 and 1, its (conditional) expected value is equal to the (conditional) probability that \(y=1\):

\(E(y|x) = 0 \times P(y = 0|x) + 1 \times P(y = 1|x) = P(y=1|x)\)

An important class of models specifies the success probability as

\(P(y = 1 | x) = G(\beta_0 + \beta_1 + \dots \beta_k x_k) = G(\boldsymbol{x} \boldsymbol{\beta})\)

The following table is taken from \citet{dalpiaz2016} and summarizes three examples of a generalized linear model:

& Linear Regression & Poisson Regression & Logistic Regression \\
\midrule

\(Y \mid {\bf X} = {\bf x}\) & \(N(\mu({\bf x}), \sigma^2)\) & \(\text{Pois}(\lambda({\bf x}))\) & \(\text{Bern}(p({\bf x}))\) \\
\textbf{Distribution Name} & Normal & Poisson & Bernoulli (Binomial) \\
\(\text{E}[Y \mid {\bf X} = {\bf x}]\) & \(\mu({\bf x})\) & \(\lambda({\bf x})\) & \(p({\bf x})\) \\
\textbf{Support} & Real: \((-\infty, \infty)\) & Integer: \(0, 1, 2, \ldots\) & Integer: \(0, 1\) \\
\textbf{Usage} & Numeric Data & Count (Integer) Data & Binary (Class ) Data \\
\textbf{Link Name} & Identity & Log & Logit \\
\textbf{Link Function} & \(\eta({\bf x}) = \mu({\bf x})\) & \(\eta({\bf x}) = \log(\lambda({\bf x}))\) & \(\eta({\bf x}) = \log \left(\frac{p({\bf x})}{1 - p({\bf x})} \right)\) \\
\textbf{Mean Function} & \(\mu({\bf x}) = \eta({\bf x})\) & \(\lambda({\bf x}) = e^{\eta({\bf x})}\) & \(p({\bf x}) = \frac{e^{\eta({\bf x})}}{1 + e^{\eta({\bf x})}} = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-\eta({\bf x})}}\) \\
\bottomrule
\end{longtable}

Like ordinary linear regression, we will seek to ``fit'' the model by estimating the \(\beta\) parameters. To do so, we will use the method of maximum likelihood.

Note that a Bernoulli distribution is a specific case of a binomial distribution where the \(n\) parameter of a binomial is \(1\). Binomial regression is also possible, but we'll focus on the much more popular Bernoulli case.

So, in general, GLMs relate the mean of the response to a linear combination of the predictors, \(\eta({\bf x})\), through the use of a link function, \(g()\). That is,

\[
\eta({\bf x}) = g\left(\text{E}[Y \mid {\bf X} = {\bf x}]\right).
\]

The mean is then

\[
\text{E}[Y \mid {\bf X} = {\bf x}] = g^{-1}(\eta({\bf x})).
\]

The estimated coefficient \emph{educ} can be interpreted as: an additional year of schooling increases the probability that a woman is in the labor force \emph{ceteris paribus} by 4\%.

One problem with linear probability models is that \(P(y=1|x)\) is specified as a linear function of the regressors. By construction, there are more or less realistic combinations of regressor values that yield \(\hat{y} < 0\) or \(\hat{y} > 1\).

Predictions for two ``extreme'' women:

              \AttributeTok{age=}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{52}\NormalTok{),}\AttributeTok{kidslt6=}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{),}\AttributeTok{kidsge6=}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{))}
\FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(linprob,xpred)}
         \DecValTok{1}          \DecValTok{2} 
\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\FloatTok{0.4104582}  \FloatTok{1.0428084} 
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{logit}{%
\section{Logit}\label{logit}}

For binary response models, the most widely used specification for G are

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  the \textbf{probit} model with \(G(z) = \phi(z)\), the standard cdf and
\item
  the \textbf{logit} model with \(G(z) = \Lambda(z) = \frac{exp(z)}{1+ exp(z)}\), the cdf of the logistic distribution.
\end{itemize}

In R many generalized linear models can be estimated by the \texttt{glm()} command. It accepts the additional option

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{family\ =\ binomial\ (link\ =\ logit)} for the logit model or
\item
  \texttt{family\ =\ binomial\ (link\ =\ probit)} for the probit model
\end{itemize}

From this table, we learn that the coefficient for age is -0.088 for logit and -0.053 for probit, respectively. In both cases, this tells us that the impact of an additional year of age on the probability of working is negative. However, we cannot straightforwardly read off the magnitude of the effect.

\hypertarget{marginal-partial-effects}{%
\section{Marginal (partial) effects}\label{marginal-partial-effects}}

Several packages provide estimates of marginal effects for different types of models. Among these are \textbf{car}, \textbf{alr3}, \textbf{mfx}, \textbf{erer}, among others. Unfortunately, none of these packages implement marginal effects correctly (i.e., correctly account for interrelated variables such as interaction terms (e.g., a:b) or power terms (e.g., I(a\^{}2)) and the packages all implement quite different interfaces for different types of models. The \textbf{margins} and \textbf{prediction} packages are a combined effort to calculate marginal effects that include complex terms and provide a uniform interface for doing those calculations.

To know how much a variable influences the labour force participation, one has to use \texttt{margins()} command:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{effects\_logit\_participation }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ margins}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{margins}\NormalTok{(logitres) }
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{summary}\NormalTok{(effects\_logit\_participation)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{multinomial-logit}{%
\section{Multinomial Logit}\label{multinomial-logit}}

A relatively common R function that fits multinomial logit models is \texttt{multinom()} from package \textbf{nnet}. Let us use the dataset \emph{nels\_small} for an example of how multinom works. The variable grades in this dataset is an index, with best grades represented by lower values of grade. We try to explain the choice of a secondary institution (psechoice) only by the high school grade. The variable pschoice

can take one of three values:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  psechoice = 1 no college,
\item
  psechoice = 2 two year college
\item
  psechoice = 3 four year college
\end{itemize}

Grades are ranked from A (hight grade A+) to F (lowest Grade F).

Recall that a larger numerical value of the variable grades represents a poorer academic performance. If the value of GRADES increases, the probability that high school graduates will choose a two-year or a four-year college goes down, relative to the probability of not attending college.

The usual function \texttt{predict} can calculate the predicted probabilities of choosing any of the three secondary education levels for two arbitrary grades: one at the median grade in the sample, and the other at the top fifth percent.

\NormalTok{newdat }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{grades=}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(medGrades, fifthPercentileGrades))}

\NormalTok{pred}

Choosing no college is 0.1810 for the student with median grades, but this probability is reduced to 0.0178 for students with top grades. Similarly, the probability of choosing a two-year school is 0.2856 for the average student but is 0.0966 for the better student.

\hypertarget{the-conditional-logit-model}{%
\section{The Conditional Logit Model}\label{the-conditional-logit-model}}

In the multinomial logit model all individuals faced the same external conditions and each individual's choice is only determined by an individual's circumstances or preferences. The conditional logit model allows for individuals to face individual-specific external conditions, such as the price of a product. For example, the price of Pepsi, 7-Up, and Coke is potentially different for each customer who purchases soda because customers can shop at different supermarkets and at different times.

Suppose we want to study the effect of price on an individual's decision about choosing one of three brands of soft drinks:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  pepsi
\item
  sevenup
\item
  coke
\end{itemize}

R offers several alternatives that allow fitting conditional logit models, one of which is the function \texttt{MCMCmnl()} from the package \textbf{MCMCpack} (others are, for instance, \texttt{clogit()} in the \textbf{survival} package and \texttt{mclogit()} in the \textbf{mclogit} package). The following code is adapted from \citet{Adkins2014}.

In order to estimate a multinomial logit with the MCMCpckage, the data is to brought in a specific format. It is necessary to record the individuals choice of beverage and each of the three prices he faces.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]

\NormalTok{N }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{nrow}\NormalTok{(cola)}
\NormalTok{N3 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ N}\SpecialCharTok{/}\DecValTok{3}
\NormalTok{price1 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ cola}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{price[}\FunctionTok{seq}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,N,}\AttributeTok{by=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)] }\CommentTok{\# sequence of each price and choice}
\NormalTok{price2 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ cola}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{price[}\FunctionTok{seq}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{,N,}\AttributeTok{by=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)]}
\NormalTok{price3 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ cola}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{price[}\FunctionTok{seq}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{,N,}\AttributeTok{by=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The first variable, pepsi, takes every third observation of choice starting at the first row. The variable will contain a one if the person chooses Pepsi and a zero otherwise since this is how the variable choice is coded in the data file. The next variable for Seven-Up starts at 2 and the sequence again increments by 3. Since Seven-Up codes as a 2 the ones and zeros generated by the sequence get multiplied by 2 (to become 2 or 0). Coke is coded as a 3 and its sequence of ones and zeros is multiplied by 3. The three variables are combined into a new one called bev.choice that takes the value of 1,2, or 3 depending on a person's choice of Pepsi, Seven-Up, or Coke.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{bchoice }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{rep}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"1"}\NormalTok{, N3)  }\CommentTok{\# recode the alternatives to a single variable that takes the value of 1, 2 or 3  epending on a person\textquotesingle{}s choice.}
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ (j }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{N3)\{}
  \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{(cola}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{choice[}\DecValTok{3}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{j}\DecValTok{{-}1}\NormalTok{]}\SpecialCharTok{==}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) bchoice[j] }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \StringTok{"2"}
  \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{(cola}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{choice[}\DecValTok{3}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{j]}\SpecialCharTok{==}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) bchoice[j] }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \StringTok{"3"}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}

\FunctionTok{library}\NormalTok{(MCMCpack)}
\NormalTok{cola.clogit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ MCMCpack}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{MCMCmnl}\NormalTok{(bchoice}\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\FunctionTok{choicevar}\NormalTok{(price1, }\StringTok{"b2"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"1"}\NormalTok{)}
                                 \SpecialCharTok{+}       \FunctionTok{choicevar}\NormalTok{(price2, }\StringTok{"b2"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"2"}\NormalTok{)}\SpecialCharTok{+}
                         \FunctionTok{choicevar}\NormalTok{(price3, }\StringTok{"b2"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"3"}\NormalTok{),}
                       \AttributeTok{baseline=}\StringTok{"3"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{mcmc.method=}\StringTok{"IndMH"}\NormalTok{)}

The output from function \texttt{multinom}gives coefficient estimates for each level of the response variable \textbf{psechoice}, except for the first level, which is the benchmark.
How a change in price affects the choice probability is different for ``own price'' changes and ``cross-price'' changes.

We can also estimate the probabilities of individual \(i\) choosing Pepsi or Sevenup for a given price.

\begin{Highlighting}[]

\CommentTok{\# The probability that individual i chooses Pepsi:}
\NormalTok{PiPepsi }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(b11}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{b2}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{pPepsi)}\SpecialCharTok{/}
\NormalTok{          (}\FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(b11}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{b2}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{pPepsi)}\SpecialCharTok{+}\FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(b12}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{b2}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{pSevenup)}\SpecialCharTok{+}
                              \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(b13}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{b2}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{pCoke))}
\CommentTok{\# The probability that individual i chooses Sevenup:}
\NormalTok{PiSevenup }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(b12}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{b2}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{pSevenup)}\SpecialCharTok{/}
\NormalTok{          (}\FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(b11}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{b2}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{pPepsi)}\SpecialCharTok{+}\FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(b12}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{b2}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{pSevenup)}\SpecialCharTok{+}
                              \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(b13}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{b2}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{pCoke))}
\CommentTok{\# The probability that individual i chooses Coke:}
\NormalTok{PiCoke }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{PiPepsi}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{PiSevenup}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The calculated probabilities are:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \(p_{i,pepsi}=0.483\)
\item
  \(p_{i,sevenup}=0.227\)
\item
  \(p_{i,coke}=0.289\)
\end{itemize}

The three probabilities are different for different individuals because different individuals face different prices; in a more complex model other regressors may be included, some of which may reflect individual characteristics.

\hypertarget{ordered-choice-models}{%
\section{Ordered Choice Models}\label{ordered-choice-models}}

The order of choices in these models is meaningful, unlike the multinomial and conditional logit model we have studied so far. The following example explains the choice of higher education, when the choice variable is psechoice and the only regressor is grades; the dataset, \emph{nels\_small} , is already known to us.

The R package \textbf{MCMCpack} is again used here, with its function \texttt{MCMCoprobit()}.

We treat PSECHOICE as an ordered variable with 1 representing the least favored alternative (no college) and 3 denoting the most favored alternative (four-year college).

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{nels.oprobit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{MCMCoprobit}\NormalTok{(psechoice }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ grades, }
                            \AttributeTok{data=}\NormalTok{nels\_small, }\AttributeTok{mcmc=}\DecValTok{10000}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{sOprobit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{summary}\NormalTok{(nels.oprobit)}
\NormalTok{tabOprobit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ sOprobit}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{statistics[, }\DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]}
\FunctionTok{kable}\NormalTok{(tabOprobit, }\AttributeTok{digits=}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{align=}\StringTok{"c"}\NormalTok{,}
      \AttributeTok{caption=}\StringTok{"Ordered probit estimates for the \textquotesingle{}nels\textquotesingle{} problem"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{table}

\caption{\label{tab:unnamed-chunk-165}Ordered probit estimates for the 'nels' problem}
\centering
\begin{tabular}[t]{l|c|c}
\hline
  & Mean & SD\\
\hline
(Intercept) & 2.9542 & 0.1478\\
\hline
grades & -0.3074 & 0.0193\\
\hline
gamma2 & 0.8616 & 0.0487\\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The results from MCMCoprobit can be translated into the textbook notations as follows:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \(\mu_1\) =− (Intercept)
\item
  \(\beta\) = grades
\item
  \(\mu_2\) = gamma2 − (Intercept) (2.9542- 0.8616)
\end{itemize}

The probabilities for each choice can be calculated as in the next code fragment:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{  mu1 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{tabOprobit[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{  b }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ tabOprobit[}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{  mu2 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ tabOprobit[}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{]}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{tabOprobit[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{  xGrade }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{(nels\_small}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{grades), }
              \FunctionTok{quantile}\NormalTok{(nels\_small}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{grades, }\FloatTok{0.05}\NormalTok{))}
  
  \CommentTok{\# Probabilities:}
\NormalTok{  prob1 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{pnorm}\NormalTok{(mu1}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{b}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{xGrade)}
\NormalTok{  prob2 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{pnorm}\NormalTok{(mu2}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{b}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{xGrade)}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\FunctionTok{pnorm}\NormalTok{(mu1}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{b}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{xGrade)}
\NormalTok{  prob3 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\FunctionTok{pnorm}\NormalTok{(mu2}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{b}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{xGrade)}
  
  \CommentTok{\# Marginal effects:}
\NormalTok{  Dp1DGrades }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \SpecialCharTok{{-}}\FunctionTok{pnorm}\NormalTok{(mu1}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{b}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{xGrade)}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{b}
\NormalTok{  Dp2DGrades }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ (}\FunctionTok{pnorm}\NormalTok{(mu1}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{b}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{xGrade)}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\FunctionTok{pnorm}\NormalTok{(mu2}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{b}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{xGrade))}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{b}
\NormalTok{  Dp3DGrades }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{pnorm}\NormalTok{(mu2}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{b}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{xGrade)}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{b}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

For instance, the marginal effect of grades on the probability of attending a four-year college for a student with average grade (6.64) and for a student in the top 5 percent (2.635) are, respectively, -0.143 and -0.031. These are similar magnitudes as in the the multinomial logit example.

\hypertarget{count-data-the-poisson-regression-model}{%
\section{Count data: The Poisson Regression Model}\label{count-data-the-poisson-regression-model}}

Instead of just 0/1-coded binary data, count data can take any non-negative integer \(0, 1, 2, \dots\). If they take very large numbers (like the number of students in a school), they can be approximated reasonably well as continuous variables in a linear models and estimated using OLS. If the numbers are relatively small, this approximation might not work well.

The Poisson regression model is the most basic and convenient model explicitly model explicitly designed for count data.

Poisson regression models can be estimated in R via the \texttt{glm()} function with the specification \textbf{family= poisson}

Estimating the model with \textbf{quasipoisson} is to adjust for potential violations of the Poisson distribution.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
  \FunctionTok{data}\NormalTok{(crime1, }\AttributeTok{package=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}wooldridge\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
  
  \CommentTok{\# Estimate linear model}
\NormalTok{  lm.res      }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}  \FunctionTok{lm}\NormalTok{(narr86}\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{pcnv}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{avgsen}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{tottime}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ptime86}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{qemp86}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{inc86}\SpecialCharTok{+}
\NormalTok{                       black}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{hispan}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{born60, }\AttributeTok{data=}\NormalTok{crime1)}
  \CommentTok{\# Estimate Poisson model}
\NormalTok{  Poisson.res }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{glm}\NormalTok{(narr86}\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{pcnv}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{avgsen}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{tottime}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ptime86}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{qemp86}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{inc86}\SpecialCharTok{+}
\NormalTok{                       black}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{hispan}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{born60, }\AttributeTok{data=}\NormalTok{crime1, }\AttributeTok{family=}\NormalTok{poisson)}
  \CommentTok{\# Quasi{-}Poisson model}
\NormalTok{  QPoisson.res}\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{glm}\NormalTok{(narr86}\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{pcnv}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{avgsen}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{tottime}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ptime86}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{qemp86}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{inc86}\SpecialCharTok{+}
\NormalTok{                       black}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{hispan}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{born60, }\AttributeTok{data=}\NormalTok{crime1, }\AttributeTok{family=}\NormalTok{quasipoisson)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{corner-solution-response-the-tobit-model}{%
\section{Corner Solution Response: The Tobit Model}\label{corner-solution-response-the-tobit-model}}

Corner solutions describe situations where the variable of interest is continuous but restricted in range. Typically, it cannot be negative.

The package \textbf{censReg} offers the command \texttt{censReg()} for estimating a Tobit model.

We have already estimated labor supply modelled for the women in the dataset \emph{mroz}, ignoring the fact that the hours worked is necessarily non-negative.

\hypertarget{censored-and-truncated-regression-models}{%
\section{Censored and Truncated Regression Models}\label{censored-and-truncated-regression-models}}

Censored regression models are closely related to Tobit models. In the basic Tobit model we observe \(y = y^*\) in the ``uncensored'' cases with \(y^* > 0\) and we only know an upper bound for \(y^* \le 0\) if we observe \$y 0 = \$.

\hypertarget{the-heckman-or-sample-selection-model}{%
\section{The Heckman, or Sample Selection Model}\label{the-heckman-or-sample-selection-model}}

The models are useful when the sample selection is not random, but whether an individual is in the sample depends on individual characteristics. For example, when studying wage determination for married women, some women are not in the labour force, therefore their wages are zero.

The Heckit procedure involves two steps, estimating both the selection equation and the equation of interest. Function \texttt{selection()} in the \textbf{sampleSelection} package performs both steps; therefore, it needs both equations among its arguments. (The selection equation is, in fact, a probit model.)

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{data}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"mroz"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{package=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}wooldridge\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

As comparison we estimate a linear model

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# OLS: log wage regression on observed data (LF participants only)}
\NormalTok{wage.lm\_obs }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{lm}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(wage)}\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{educ}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{exper, }
              \AttributeTok{data=}\FunctionTok{subset}\NormalTok{(mroz, inlf}\SpecialCharTok{==}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)) }
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

In principle, the selection equation and the wage equation could have exactly the same set of regressors. But this is usually not a good idea. To get a good estimate of the selection model, it is very desirable to have at least one variable in the selection equation that acts like an instrument: that is, a variable that one expects would affect the selection process, but not the wage process, except through selection. In this example, the kids variable might play such a role, if we can assume that women with kids may be more likely to be stay-at-home moms, but for working moms having kids would not affect their hourly pay rate.

\begin{Shaded}

As you can see, the selection corrections did not have a big effect on any of the parameters of interest. The estimated returns to education and experience are a bit larger in the selection regressions, but the difference is really small. The OLS estimates diverge more from the Heckit estimates, indicating a bias stemming from a sample selection problem. The 2-stage model also provides the estimated coefficient on the inverse Mills ratio is given for the Heckman model. The fact that it is weakly statistically different from zero is consistent with the idea that selection bias might be a problem in this case.
I don't know if marginal effects can be calculated directly from the sampleSelection object. Calculation marginal for the model selection separately can be easily done though.
